 | Artist\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Title\n|-\n| 2017\n| [[Carlos Vives]]<ref name=\"eonline.com\">{{cite web|title=Carlos Vives Premieres Music Video for \"Al Filo de Tu Amor\" Featuring Ariadna Guti\u00e9rrez|url=http://www.eonline.com/news/823827/carlos-vives-premieres-music-video-for-al-filo-de-tu-amor-featuring-ariadna-gutierrez|website=eonline.com|accessdate=23 January 2017}}</ref>\n| [[Carlos Vives discography|Al Filo de Tu Amor]]<ref name=\"eonline.com\" />\n|}\n\n==In popular culture==\nAriadna Guti\u00e9rrez was impersonated by James Leyva, stage name \"[[Valentina (drag queen)|Valentina]],\" on season 9, episode 6 of ''[[RuPaul's Drag Race (season 9)|RuPaul's Drag Race]]''.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.srtacolombia.org/ Official Miss Colombia website]\n* {{IMDb name|7803367}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-ach}}\n{{S-bef|before={{flagicon|USA}} [[Nia Sanchez]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Miss Universe]] 1st Runner-Up\n|years=[[Miss Universe 2015|2015]]}}\n{{S-aft|after={{flagicon|Haiti}} [[Raquel P\u00e9lissier]]}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[File:Flag of Atl\u00e1ntico.svg|border|22x20px|Atl\u00e1ntico]] [[Paulina Vega]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Miss Colombia]]\n|years=2014}}\n{{S-aft|after=[[File:Flag of Choc\u00f3.svg|border|22x20px|Choc\u00f3]] [[Andrea Tovar]]}}\n{{S-bef|before=Andrea Pe\u00f1uela}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Sucre Department|Miss Sucre]]\n|years=2014}}\n{{S-aft|after=Paula Correa}}\n{{S-end}}\n{{Miss Universe 2015 delegates}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gutierrez, Ariadna}}\n[[Category:1993 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century Colombian actresses]]\n[[Category:Colombian beauty pageant winners]]\n[[Category:Colombian expatriates in the United States]]\n[[Category:Colombian female models]]\n[[Category:Colombian film actresses]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Miss Colombia winners]]\n[[Category:Miss Universe 2015 contestants]]\n[[Category:Participants in American reality television series]]\n[[Category:People from Barranquilla]]\n[[Category:People from Sucre Department]]\n", "name_user": "Inter&anthro", "label": "safe", "comment": "more specific", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ariadna_Guti%C3%A9rrez"}
{"title_page": "Oxford West and Abingdon (UK Parliament constituency)", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=June 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2017}}\n{{Infobox UK constituency main\n |name        = Oxford West and Abingdon\n |parliament  = uk\n |map1        = OxfordWestAbingdon2007\n |map2        = EnglandOxfordshire\n |map_entity  = [[Oxfordshire]]\n |map_year    = \n |year        = 1983\n |abolished   = \n |type        = County\n |elects_howmany = One\n |previous    = [[Oxford (UK Parliament constituency)|Oxford]], [[Abingdon (UK Parliament constituency)|Abingdon]]\n |next        = \n |towns = [[Abingdon-on-Thames|Abingdon]], [[Kidlington]], [[Oxford]] (5 wards), [[Radley]]\n |electorate  = 76,953 (December 2019)<ref>{{cite news |title=Oxford West & Abingdon - Election 2019 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/E14000874 |accessdate=18 December 2019 |publisher=BBC News |date=13 December 2019}}</ref>\n |mp          = [[Layla Moran]]\n |party       = Liberal Democrats (UK)\n |region      = England\n |county      = [[Oxfordshire]]\n |european    = South East England\n}}\n\n'''Oxford West and Abingdon''' is a [[List of United Kingdom Parliament constituencies|parliamentary constituency]] in the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]].{{#tag:ref|A [[county constituency]] (for the purposes of election expenses and type of returning officer)|group= n}}{{#tag:ref|As with all constituencies, the constituency elects one Member of Parliament (MP) by the [[first past the post]] system of election at least every five years.|group= n}}\n\n==History==\n===Creation===\nThe seat was created in [[1983 United Kingdom general election|1983]] as part of the reconfiguration of those in the county to avoid [[malapportionment]], abolishing [[Oxford (UK Parliament constituency)|Oxford]] as a seat. It merged about half the city with the east of the former [[Abingdon (UK Parliament constituency)|Abingdon]] seat.\n\n===MPs===\nThe [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] [[John Patten, Baron Patten|John Patten]] (MP for Oxford in the [[1979 United Kingdom general election|1979]]\u201383 Parliament), held the seat from its creation until he retired in [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997]]. The seat was gained by the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrat]], [[Evan Harris|Dr Evan Harris]], who held the seat for thirteen years until the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 general election]], when the Conservative [[Nicola Blackwood]] retook the seat in one of the most [[marginal seat|marginal]] results of that election. Blackwood held the seat until the [[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017 general election]] when she was defeated by Liberal Democrat [[Layla Moran]] in another marginal result.\n\n===Contests===\nThe seat has been contested nine times, each of them general elections. At each contest the Labour party candidate has polled third&mdash;the peak share of votes to date being 20.2%, in 1997. The strongest victory, in share of the vote, was that of Dr Harris of the Liberal Democrats in 2001, a 17.8% majority (in a seven-way contest).\n\nThe Green or predecessor Ecology Party stood in the first eight contests, in each losing the [[deposit (politics)|deposit]] paid.\n\n==Economic profile==\nThe constituency includes the town of [[Abingdon, Oxfordshire|Abingdon]], the village of [[Kidlington]], and the western and northern parts of the city of [[Oxford]], as well as a minority of the [[colleges of the University of Oxford]] \u2013 the constituency covering the rest of the city being [[Oxford East]]. At the end of 2010 unemployment was the fifth lowest of the 84 South East constituencies (measure used: claimant count), at 1.2% compared to a mean of 2.45%.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/news/datablog/2010/nov/17/unemployment-and-employment-statistics-economics Unemployment claimants by constituency] ''[[The Guardian]]''</ref> The area has rapid transit connections to London, [[Reading, Berkshire|Reading]] and the commercial heart of Oxford, has large business and research parks and a choice of two major railway stations, {{rws|Oxford}} and {{rws|Didcot Parkway}}.\n\n==Boundaries and boundary changes==\n;1983\u20131997\n: The District of Vale of White Horse wards of Abbey, Caldecott, Cumnor, Fitzharris, Hinksey, Kennington, Northcourt, Ock, Radley, St Helen Without, and Sunningwell and Wootton, and the City of Oxford wards of Central, Cherwell, North, South, West, and Wolvercote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/1983/417/contents/made/data.htm|title=The Parliamentary Constituencies (England) Order 1983|website=www.legislation.gov.uk|access-date=2019-02-13}}</ref>\n:The majority of the new constituency, comprising the town of [[Abingdon-on-Thames]] and areas to the west of Oxford, was previously part of the abolished County Constituency of [[Abingdon (UK Parliament constituency)|Abingdon]] in [[Berkshire]].  The [[Oxford|City of Oxford]] wards had previously been in the abolished Borough Constituency of [[Oxford (UK Parliament constituency)|Oxford]].\n\n'''1997\u20132010'''\n\n: The District of Vale of White Horse wards of Abbey, Caldecott, Cumnor, Fitzharris, Hinksey, Kennington, Northcourt, Ock, Radley, St Helen Without, and Sunningwell and Wootton, the City of Oxford wards of Central, Cherwell, North, West, and Wolvercote, and the District of Cherwell wards of Gosford, North West Kidlington, and South East Kidlington.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/1995/1626/made/data.htm|title=The Parliamentary Constituencies (England) Order 1995|website=www.legislation.gov.uk|language=en|access-date=2019-02-13}}</ref>\n:[[Kidlington]] transferred from [[Witney (UK Parliament constituency)|Witney]].  The South ward of the City of Oxford transferred to [[Oxford East (UK Parliament constituency)|Oxford East]].\n\n'''Since 2010'''\n\n: The District of Vale of White Horse wards of Abingdon Abbey and Barton, Abingdon Caldecott, Abingdon Dunmore, Abingdon Fitzharris, Abingdon Northcourt, Abingdon Ock Meadow, Abingdon Peachcroft, Appleton and Cumnor, Kennington and South Hinksey, North Hinksey and Wytham, Radley, and Sunningwell and Wootton, the City of Oxford wards of Jericho and Osney, North, St Margaret's, Summertown, and Wolvercote, and the District of Cherwell wards of Kidlington North, Kidlington South, and Yarnton, Gosford and Water Eaton.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/2007/1681/made/data.htm|title=The Parliamentary Constituencies (England) Order 2007|website=www.legislation.gov.uk|access-date=2019-02-13}}</ref>\n:Further loss to Oxford East, including the city centre, following revision of City of Oxford wards.  Marginal realignment of boundary with [[Wantage (UK Parliament constituency)|Wantage]]. [[Yarnton]] transferred from Witney.\n\n==Changes proposed by the Boundary Commission==\nThe [[Boundary Commission for England]] submitted their final proposals in respect of the [[Sixth Periodic Review of Westminster constituencies|Sixth Periodic Review of Westminster Constituencies]] (the 2018 review) in September 2018 which would reduce the total number of MPs from 650 to 600. Although the proposals were immediately laid before [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|Parliament]] they were not brought forward by the [[Government of the United Kingdom|Government]] for approval. Accordingly, they will '''not''' come into effect for the [[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019 election]] due to take place on 12 December 2019, which will be contested using the constituency boundaries in place since 2010.\n\nThe Commission proposed to extend the constituency both northwards, adding the [[Cherwell District|District of Cherwell]] ward of [[Kirtlington]] from [[Henley (UK Parliament constituency)|Henley]], and southwards, adding the [[Vale of White Horse|Vale of White Horse District]] wards of [[Drayton, Vale of White Horse|Drayton]] and [[Marcham]] from [[Wantage (UK Parliament constituency)|Wantage]]. Two further [[Oxford|City of Oxford]] wards (Jericho and Osney, and North) would be transferred to [[Oxford East (UK Parliament constituency)|Oxford East]] (to be renamed Oxford), leaving just three (of 24) wards in the constituency.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bce2018.org.uk/publications|title=Final recommendations report|last=Boundary Commission for England, 2018 Review, Associated consultation documents|date=September 2018}}</ref>\n\nIt was proposed that the constituency be renamed Abingdon and North Oxford.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Members of Parliament ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Election\n!Member<ref>{{rayment-hc|o|date=March 2012}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/E14000874|title=Oxford West & Abingdon parliamentary constituency - Election 2017|work=BBC News|access-date=2017-06-26|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n!colspan=\"2\"|Party\n|-\n| [[1983 United Kingdom general election|1983]]\n| [[John Patten, Baron Patten|John Patten]]\n{{Party name with colour|Conservative Party (UK)}}\n|-\n| [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997]]\n| [[Evan Harris]]\n{{Party name with colour|Liberal Democrats (UK)}}\n|-\n| [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010]]\n| [[Nicola Blackwood]]\n{{Party name with colour|Conservative Party (UK)}}\n|-\n| [[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017]]\n| [[Layla Moran]]\n{{Party name with colour|Liberal Democrats (UK)}}\n|}\n\n== Elections ==\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" heights=\"271\">\nFile:OxfordwestandAbingdon.svg|'''Election results for Oxford West and Abingdon'''\n</gallery>\n\n=== Elections in the 2010s ===\n\n{{Election box begin|\n|title=[[2019 United Kingdom general election|General election 2019]]: Oxford West and Abingdon<ref>{{cite web |title=Oxford West & Abingdon Parliamentary constituency |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/E14000874 |website=BBC News |publisher=BBC |accessdate=27 November 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n{{El